Under French law possession of movable things is lost as soon as they have c
eased to be under the power or control of the possessor. Possession of wild animals is lost as soon as they have acquired their freedom. Possession of tamed animas such as bees and pigeons is lost when they cease to return habitually to their hives or dov
ecotes, or when they lose their animus revertendi, i.e., \lquote their intention/habit to return\rquote .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid16266356\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 Possession of immovab
le things can be preserved solo-animo, i.e., it is not lost just because the possessor has voluntarily abstained, for a time, from material or physical acts of possession or has been incapable to exercise them because he was too far away, or because of th
e nature of the immovable, or because of some temporary obstacle. However, abnormally long intervals between acts of possession, taking in to account the nature of the thing, may be considered as a tacit renunciation.  Art 1142 of the Civil Code.}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid16266356\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 Furtherm
ore, possession is not necessarily lost just because a third person has occupied the immovable. It shall be lost only if he occupies the immovable for a year. / Arts 1142 and 1149 of the Civil Code/.  If the former possessor lets this period elapse }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid16266356\charrsid12875540 without}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
 any act of enjoyment or any claim for return of possession, whether he did or did not know of the adverse occupancy, he shall lose his right of possession. This is true even if he manifested his intention to continue in possession by acts such as the pay
