\tx-3480\jclisttab\tx360\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls13\ilvl1\adjustright\rin0\lin270\itap0\pararsid11346195 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 The obligation to up-keep the thing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 
\ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 : - The usufructuary has an obligation to have regular maintenance and repair works done at his cost. See Art 1
313 of the Civil Code. He also has an obligation to inform the bare owner where the thing requires major or considerable repairs where he is not at fault for such damage or deterioration of the thing that made such repair necessary. However, he will be li
able for considerable or major repairs, if they became necessary because of deterioration due to his fault, i.e., damages resulting from failure of the usufructuary to have regular maintenance and repair works done. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 Considerable or major repairs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540  are repairs
 that require expenses that are greater than the average annual income generated by the thing. See Arts 1337 and 1338(2) of the Civil Code.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 4.\tab}}\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-240\li270\ri0\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx-1440\jclisttab\tx360\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls13\ilvl1\adjustright\rin0\lin270\itap0\pararsid11346195 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 The usufructuary }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 has an obligation to pay all the charges encumbering the profits}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540  of the thing such as annual tax
es such as land tax, building tax or income taxes and other charges that are normally payable out of the income derived from the thing. See Art 1314 of the Civil Code. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 5.\tab}The usufractuary has }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
an obligation to inform the bare owner about any act }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid12262087\charrsid12875540 of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 interfe
rence by a third person in the rights of the bare owner}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
. For instance, he must inform the bare owner of any person, whether in court or out side of a court, challenging the right of ownership of the bare owner over the thing. Where a usufructuary fails to 
comply with this provision and the bare owner loses his right of ownership, he shall be liable to compensate the bare owner as if he himself caused the loss or damage of the rights of the bare owner. See Art 1342 of the Civil Code. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid13435518\charrsid12875540  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 On the other hand, the 
usufructuary as a possessor of the thing, shall have a right to bring possessory action and to use force to protect his possession in case where any person, including the bare owner, interferes with his possession of the thing. See Arts 1341, 1148 and 114
9 of the Civil Code. The usufructuary will also have the right of usufruct over the compensation paid in case where the thing is lost or destroyed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\super\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 
\ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 1319(2) 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx-3480\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11346195 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 6. The usufructuary has }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 an obligation, at the time of extinction of the usufruct, to restore or restitute the thing to the bare owner or his agent}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
. He shall be liable for the loss or deterioration of the thing, where the loss or deterioration resulted from his fault, such as abuse of the thing or failure to exercise due care in the use of the thing or neg
ligence in the use and management of the thing, failure to make necessary or normal repairs\'85See Arts 1317 of the Civil Code.  
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s2\qj \li0\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11346195 \rtlch\fcs1 \ab\ai\af1\afs28\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\i\f1\fs28\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ai0\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i0\f0\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 {\*\bkmkstart _Toc175128729}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc204104784}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc229915067}
RIGHTS AND OBLIGATIONS OF THE BARE OWNER{\*\bkmkend _Toc175128729}{\*\bkmkend _Toc204104784}{\*\bkmkend _Toc229915067}
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 1.\tab}}\pard\plain \ltrpar
\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls14\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11346195 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 
\ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
He has the duty to refrain from any kind of interference with the right of the usufructuary to possess, use and enjoy the thing and collect and use its fruits. For example, he cannot change the thing, which is subject of the usufruct nor can he use or exp
loit the thing or interfere with the possession of the thing.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 2.\tab}He must undertake major repairs as defined under Arts 1337 and 1338, which are not result of the usufructuary\rquote 
s fault. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 3.\tab}He has an obligation to cover extra ordinary charges. Art 1315 
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s2\qj \li0\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11346195 \rtlch\fcs1 \ab\ai\af1\afs28\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\i\f1\fs28\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ai0\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i0\f0\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 {\*\bkmkstart _Toc175128730}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc204104785}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc229915068}EXTINCTION OF USUFRUCT
{\*\bkmkend _Toc175128730}{\*\bkmkend _Toc204104785}{\*\bkmkend _Toc229915068}
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}\pard\plain \ltrpar
\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls98\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11346195 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 
\ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 The right of usufruct shall be extinguished for either of the following reasons;  
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 1.\tab}}\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx360\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls15\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11346195 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 Death of the usufructuary}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 
\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
- a right of usufruct is some times called a personal servitude because it depends on the life of the usufructuary. In other words, the right of usufruct shall terminate up on the death of the usufructuary.  See Art 1322(1) 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 2.\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 Lapse of the period for whic
h it is created}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 . For example, a usufruct created for a period of five years shall terminate at the end of the five years. Art 1322(1)
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 3.\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 Extinctive prescription}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540  \endash  lack of exercise of any of the usufruct rights or complete absence enjoyment, use possession 
by the usufructuary or by his agent in relation to chattels/ ordinary corporeal movable things/ shall result in the termination of usufruct. See Art 1310 cum 1192 of the Civil Code.    
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 4.\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 The loss or destruction of the thing;}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540  Similar to the case of loss o
f ownership right, usufruct shall also be extinguished as a result of the loss or destruction of the object of property. See Arts 1319, 1310 cum 1188 of the Civil Code.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 5.\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
Consolidation or merger of the position of the bare owner and the usufructuary in one person}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
 shall also result in the extinction of usufruct right. This happens when the usufructuary acquires bare ownership (by contract or succession) or when the bare owner acquires the usufruct by contract. See Arts 1676/1/ cum 1842 of the Civil Code.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 6.\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
Forfeiture or waiver of right by the usufructuary}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
; A right of usufruct of chattels shall be extinguished where the usufructuary expresses, clearly and unequivocally, his intention to waive his rights as a usufructuary. See Arts 1310 cum1191 of the Civil C
ode. Refer also to Art 1676/1/ cum 1825 of the Civil Code. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}\pard \ltrpar
\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls98\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11346195 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 Acquisitive prescription in favor of a third party}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid13435518\charrsid12875540 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
 the right of usufruct shall be extinguished as a result of acquisition of usufruct right on the thing in favor of another person. See Art 1310 cum 1168 of the Civil Code.
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s2\qj \li0\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11346195 \rtlch\fcs1 \ab\ai\af1\afs28\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\i\f1\fs28\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ai0\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i0\f0\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 {\*\bkmkstart _Toc175128731}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc204104786}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc229915069}RIGHT OF USE AND HABITATION}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \ai0\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i0\f0\insrsid13435518\charrsid12875540 {\*\bkmkstart _Toc175128732}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc204104787}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc229915070}{\*\bkmkend _Toc175128731}{\*\bkmkend _Toc204104786}{\*\bkmkend _Toc229915069}
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \s2 \rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 1.\tab}}\pard \ltrpar\s2\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx360\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls15\ilvl3\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11346195 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ai0\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i0\f0\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 RIGHT OF USE{\*\bkmkend _Toc175128732}
{\*\bkmkend _Toc204104787}{\*\bkmkend _Toc229915070}
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}\pard\plain \ltrpar
\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls98\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11346195 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 
\ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 Right of use is a tempora
ry real right (for agreed period of time or for life the beneficiary) which entitles the beneficiary, called the user, to use a thing of another person and to receive its fruits such as profits or rents\'85
 but only with in the limits of his own and his family's needs.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid13435518\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
Right of use may be created by an agreement, with or without consideration, or by will.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid13435518\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
The right of use is not recognized under the Ethiopian Civil Code; hence we shall briefly see the rights and obligations of the user under the French Civil Code.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid13435518\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
The rights and obligations of the user are governed by the instrument that created the use right, but in the absence of such provisions in the instrument the user will have the following rights and obligations. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 1)\tab}}\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx360\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls31\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11346195 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
The user has the right to the profits or fruits of the thing proportional to his and his family's needs. He can claim the various fruits or produce only in an amount in which each kind of produce will be consumed by him and his family, i.e., spouse, child
ren and servants. However, collateral family members and ascendants are not included. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 2)\tab}
 The user has the same duties as a usufructuary. Please, read the discussion regarding the duties of the usufructuary.  
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 3)\tab}The user cannot transfer, assign or lease h
is right, or substitute a third party, hence, the right of use may not be seized by the creditors of the user, even if it was constituted for consideration. But he can sell a portion of the fruits, which he acquired in ownership by taking them directly or
 having them delivered. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}\pard \ltrpar
\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls99\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11346195 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
The right of use is extinguished in the same manner as the right of usufruct is extinguished.
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc175128734}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc204104789}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc229915071}{\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 2.\tab}}\pard \ltrpar
\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls15\ilvl3\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11346195 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
RIGHT OF HABITATION /OCCUPATION OF PREMISES}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 {\*\bkmkend _Toc175128734}{\*\bkmkend _Toc204104789}/}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
{\*\bkmkend _Toc229915071}
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}\pard \ltrpar
\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls99\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11346195 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 This rig
ht is merely a particular type of right of use, i.e., a right of use exercised over residential houses or premises. Hence, the rules discussed in relation to usufruct and use rights are applicable to the right of habitation or right of occupation of premi
ses. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid3692480\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
Normally, the physical scope of the right of habitation is determined by the instrument creating it. Unless there are restrictions or reservations in the instrument, the right of habitation includes the whole house, which is its object and all its a
ccessories. However, the beneficiary must not exercise his right beyond the needs of his and his family's residence. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid3692480\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
Art 1353 of the Civil Code defines the rig
ht of habitation or right of occupation of premises as a right to live in a house or part of a house belonging to another person. The beneficiary of the right of habitation has the right to live in the house with his/her spouse, direct ascendants, descend
ants and servants. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid3692480\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
The beneficiary of right of habitation whose right is limited to part of a house also has the right to use parts of the building/house and the compound that are intended for the common use of all occupiers of the building. See Art 1355 of the Civil Code.}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid3692480\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
The beneficiary of the right of habitation has an obligation to cover costs required for regular repairs and maintenance of the house in which he lives. However, where his right is limited to part of the building and the owner occupie
s the other part of the building such expenses are to be covered by the owner of the house. See Art 1356 of the Civil Code.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid3692480\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
Similar to the rights of usufruct and use, a right of habitation is personal to the beneficiary and hence cannot be transferred and may not pass to his heirs. See Art 1357 of the Civil Code. 
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj \li0\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11346195 \rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs32\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\fs32\lang1033\langfe1033\kerning32\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 {\*\bkmkstart _Toc175128736}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc194062745}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc204104791}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc229915073}
UNIT SIX{\*\bkmkstart _Toc175128737}{\*\bkmkend _Toc175128736}- SERVITUDE{\*\bkmkend _Toc194062745}{\*\bkmkend _Toc204104791}{\*\bkmkend _Toc175128737}{\*\bkmkend _Toc229915073}
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}\pard\plain \ltrpar
\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls104\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11346195 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 
\ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 Servitude is a right in rem / real right/ 
over a definite plot of land, called the servient tenement and annexed to another plot of land, called the dominant tenement. In other words, it is a property right vested in the owner/holder of one plot of land to use a land belonging to another for cert
ain purposes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid7624157\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
Servitude is a right that can only exist in relation to two or more plots of land belonging to two or more persons. However, these lands are not required to be adjacent. French and German Laws do require that the servient and dominant tenem
ents be adjacent. See Art 1359(1) (2) of the Civil Code. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid7624157\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
Servitude may also be defined as an encumbrance or restriction on the right of ownership of the owner of the servient tenement for the benefit of the owner of dominant tenement. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid7624157\charrsid12875540 

\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 Furthermo
re, it is held that the right of servitude may be created only for the benefit of another land. This is intended to prevent creation of servitude for the benefit if of an individual or group, which could consist of an obligation to perform positive acts. 
Note that an obligation to perform personal services or positive acts cannot be made the subject matter of servitude. See Art 1360 and 1373 of the Civil Code.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid7624157\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
As any real right, not only the burden of servitude runs with the servient land its benefit also
 runs with the dominant land. This is the essence of a real right (servitude) as opposed to personal servitudes, such as the right of usufruct, use and habitation that are also called personal servitude. See Art 1361 of the Civil Code.}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid7624157\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 Servitude creates 
an obligation, on the owner of the servient tenement, only to refrain from preventing the owner of the dominant tenement to do certain acts that the latter would not have been able to do otherwise.  In other words, servitude shall not create an obligation
 
to perform positive acts on the owner of the servient tenement. See Art 1359/2/ of the code. One exception to this rule is provided under Art 1360 and 1373 of the Civil Code, which allows the parties to make an agreement in which the owner of the servient
 
tenement undertakes to perform works necessary for the enjoyment and preservation of the right of servitude. Such works may be construction and maintenance of pavements used by the owner of the dominant tenement to exercise his right of way, installation 
or repair of pipelines to enable the owner of the dominant tenement to have access to water ...etc.
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11346195 \rtlch\fcs1 \ab\ai\af0\afs28\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\i\fs28\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 {\*\bkmkstart _Toc175128740}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc194062748}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc204104794}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc229915076}PURPOSE OF SERVITUDE
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14772426\charrsid12875540 {\*\bkmkend _Toc175128740}{\*\bkmkend _Toc194062748}{\*\bkmkend _Toc204104794}{\*\bkmkend _Toc229915076}
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}\pard\plain \ltrpar
\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls105\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11346195 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 
\ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 A person may be unable to make the most advantageous use of his land or building }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid7624157\charrsid12875540 without}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 
\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540  some rights over the land belonging to his neighbors. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid7624157\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid7624157\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}T}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
he main purpose of servitude is to enable the owner of the dominant tenement to derive the best possible use and benefit from his land by giving him certain rights on the land belonging to another person, called servient owner.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 
\ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid6822590\charrsid12875540  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
However, unless the servitudes that may be created on a land are restricted in number and extent, it may hamper the profitable use of the servient land and gravely dim
inish its value, and this will ultimately injure public interest. This is because the owner/holder of such land can not use his land in the manner he desires and other persons will not be interested to acquire such land as their right of ownership is limi
ted or encumbered by the servitude or the right of another person.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid7624157\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 Therefore, the law tries to}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
restrict the number and extent of encumbrances or servitudes on the servient tenement in the following ways.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 1.\tab}}\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx360\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls22\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11346195 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 Servitude should be used exclusively for the pur
pose of using or exploiting the dominant land and it must be used exclusively for that purpose. In other words, the owner of the dominant tenement may not use the servient tenement for the purpose exploiting another land that is not part the dominant tene
ment. This is because servitude is created on one land for the purpose of using and enjoying another land/ the dominant tenement/, and not for the general benefit of the owner of the dominant tenement.  
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 2.\tab} The law also limits the rights of the owner of th
e dominant tenement to use the servient tenement only to purposes for which the servitude was created at its inception. In other words, it cannot be used for new purposes that may arise after the creation of the servitude. For instance, a servitude of cre
a
ted to cross a land on foot cannot be used to use cars where the owner of the dominant tenement purchases a car, because this increases the burden of the owner of the servient tenement. See Art 1376 of the Civil Code. The law also imposes various obligati
ons on the owner of the dominant tenement with the intention of the preventing him from increasing the burden of the servient tenement. Refer to Arts 1375, 1377, and 1380 of the Civil Code.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 3.\tab}The owner of the servient tenement has the right to redeem the s
ervitude where the benefits or advantages it provides to the dominant tenement are lesser than the inconveniences or damages it causes to the servient tenement. See Art 1383.         }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 
\fs28\insrsid7624157\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 4.\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
The owner of the servient tenement cannot be required to do positive acts; he may merely be required to abstain from doing something or to permit the owner of the dominant land to do something on the servient land.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 
\fs28\insrsid7624157\charrsid12875540  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 For instance, the owner of the servient tenement may be required;
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f3\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'2d\tab}}\pard \ltrpar
\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls106\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11346195 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 To abstain from building or planting trees
 so as not to obstruct view from the dominant   land, or}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid7624157\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f3\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'2d\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
 To allow the owner of the dominant tenement to walk or drive across his land, or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid7624157\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f3\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'2d\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
 To allow the owner of the dominant tenement to take water or sand or chalk from his land.     
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 5.\tab}}\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx360\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls22\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11346195 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
In order to prevent unfair and excessive burden or damages to the servient tenement, the law under Art 1365 of the Civil Code, provides that where it is not clear as to whether the provisions of a contract create a servitude running with the land or a per
sonal obligation on the owner of the land, such doubtful provisions shall be interpreted to have created a personal right or obligation and not a servitude. Also Art 1369. 
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11346195 \rtlch\fcs1 \ab\ai\af0\afs28\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\i\fs28\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 {\*\bkmkstart _Toc175128744}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc194062749}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc204104795}{\*\bkmkstart _Toc229915077}SOURCES OF SERVITUDE
{\*\bkmkend _Toc175128744}{\*\bkmkend _Toc194062749}{\*\bkmkend _Toc204104795}{\*\bkmkend _Toc229915077} 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \f10\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \loch\af10\dbch\af0\hich\f10 \'fc\tab}}\pard\plain \ltrpar
\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls107\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11346195 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 
\ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 The right of servitude may arise from a contract, a will, acquisitive prescription or the provisions of the law.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 1.\tab}}\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx360\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls27\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0\pararsid11346195 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 Ser}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 
\fs28\insrsid6822590\charrsid12875540 vitudes arising from }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid6822590\charrsid12875540 contracts}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid6822590\charrsid12875540 ; }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 
\ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 According to Art 1362/1/ of the Civil Code, a servitude may b
e created by an agreement or contract concluded between the owner/holder of the dominant tenement and the owner of the owner/holder of the servient tenement. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 2.\tab}Servitude may also arise from the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
will of the deceased}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540  person who divides his land holding bet
ween two or more persons. In other words, the testator who owns/holds a land may burden one of the lands with servitude of a certain type for the benefit of the legatee of another plot of land. See Art 1362/2/ of the Civil Code.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 3.\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 Acquisitive Prescription}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
; According to Art 1366 of the Civil Code, servitude may arise from enjoyment of the servient tenement for a period of ten years. However, this mode of acquisition applies only to apparent servitude. An apparent servitude is a servitude that requires cert
a
in external and visible or apparent structures or means for its enjoyment or exercise, which also evidence its existence. In other words, non-apparent servitudes, i.e., servitudes whose enjoyment do not require installation or construction of external or 
a
pparent materials/structures may not be acquired by acquisitive prescription of ten years. The rational behind this rule seems to be clear, because in cases of apparent servitudes the owner of the servient tenement has the opportunity to see acts of inter
f
erence by another person on his land and can object to the commission of the acts. Hence, the law does not protect a person who fails to do so for a long period. While in cases of the non-apparent servitude, the owner of the servient tenement does not hav
e an opportunity to object to such acts since he might have not known the acts of the owner of the dominant tenement. See Art 1366/2/ and 1367 of the Civil Code.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid11346195\charrsid12875540  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 However, a servitude acquired through acquisitive prescription shall not affect third parties u
nless its acquisition is registered in the register of immovable properties. For instance, the owner of the dominant tenement cannot exercise his right against the transferee of the servient tenement unless his rights are entered in the registers of immov
able properties. See Art 1368 /2/ of the Civil Code. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid7624157\charrsid12875540 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 4.\tab}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 Servitude arising out of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 provisions of the law}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs28 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid2119398\charrsid12875540 
. The contiguity of land belonging to different owners or occupied by different persons creates conflict if either or both of them wish to enjoy their
 lands without any consideration for the damages or annoyance caused to the other. These conflicts can be eliminated only by limiting the powers that the right of ownership usually involves. Specific provisions of the Civil Code, which determine what is a
llowed and what is prohibited, are intended to prevent some of these potential conflicts. Refer to the provisions of Art 1217, 1218, 1219, 1220, 1221-1224, 1245-1254, 1372/2/ of the Civil Code.
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11346195 \rtlch\fcs1 \ab\ai\af0\afs28\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
